<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" ?>
<exercises xml:id="sec_mtx_trans_exer">
  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Given matrix <m>A=\left[ \begin{array}{ccr} 1\amp 2 \amp 1 \\ 1 \amp 0 \amp -3 \end{array} \right]</m>,
        write the coordinate form of the transformation <m>T</m> defined by <m>T(\vx)=A\vx</m>.
        (Note: Writing a transformation in coordinate form refers to writing the 
        transformation in terms of the entries of the input and output vectors.)
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>
  
  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Suppose the transformation <m>T</m> is defined by <m>T(\vx)=A\vx</m> where
        <me>
          A=\left[ \begin{array}{ccr} 1\amp 1\amp -1 \\ 2\amp 1\amp 1 \\ 4\amp 1\amp 4 \end{array}  \right]
        </me>.
        Determine if <m>\vb=\left[ \begin{array}{c} 1\\0\\0 \end{array}  \right]</m> is 
        in the range of <m>T</m>.
        If so, find all <m>\vx</m>'s which map to <m>\vb</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>
  
  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Suppose <m>T</m> is a matrix transformation and
        <me>
          T(\vv_1) = \left[ \begin{array}{c} 1 \\ 2 \end{array}  \right] \, , \, T(\vv_2) = \left[ \begin{array}{r} -2 \\ 3 \end{array}  \right]
        </me>
        Find <m>T(2\vv_1 -5 \vv_2)</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>
  
  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Given a matrix transformation defined as
        <me>
          T\left( \left[ \begin{array}{c} x_1 \\ x_2 \\ x_3 \end{array}  \right] \right) = \left[ \begin{array}{c} 2x_1 -x_3 \\ -x_1 +2x_2 +x_3 \\ 3x_2 - 4x_3 \end{array}  \right]
        </me>
        determine the matrix <m>A</m> for which <m>T(\vx) = A\vx</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>
  
  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Suppose a matrix transformation <m>T</m> defined by
        <m>T(\vx)=A\vx</m> for some unknown <m>A</m> matrix satisfies
        <me>
          T\left( \left[ \begin{array}{c} 1 \\ 0 \end{array}  \right] \right) = \left[ \begin{array}{c} 2\\ 1 \end{array}  \right] \, \text{ and }  \, T\left( \left[ \begin{array}{c} 0 \\ 1 \end{array}  \right] \right) = \left[ \begin{array}{r} -1\\ 3 \end{array}  \right] \,
        </me>.
        Use the matrix transformation properties to determine <m>T(\vx)</m> where 
        <m>\vx= \left[ \begin{array}{c} x_1\\x_2 \end{array}  \right]</m>.
        Use the expression for <m>T(\vx)</m> to determine the matrix <m>A</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>
  
  <exercise>
    <introduction>
      <p>
        For each of the following matrices,
        determine if the transformation <m>T</m> defined by
        <m>T(\vx)=A\vx</m> is onto and if <m>T</m> is one-to-one.
      </p>
    </introduction>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>A=\left[ \begin{array}{ccr} 1\amp 1 \amp 1 \\ 1 \amp 2 \amp -3 \end{array} \right]</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>A=\left[ \begin{array}{ccc} 1\amp 1 \amp 2 \\ 2 \amp 2 \amp 4 \end{array} \right]</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>A=\left[ \begin{array}{rcc} 1\amp 1 \amp 2 \\ 1 \amp 2 \amp 3 \\ -1 \amp 1 \amp 2 \end{array} \right]</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>A=\left[ \begin{array}{cc} 1\amp 1 \\ 2 \amp 3 \\ 3 \amp 0 \end{array} \right]</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Come up with an example of a one-to-one transformation from <m>\R^3</m> to <m>\R^4</m>,
        if possible.
        If not, explain why not.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>
  
  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Come up with an example of an onto transformation from <m>\R^3</m> to <m>\R^4</m>,
        if possible.
        If not, explain why not.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>
  
  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Come up with an example of a one-to-one but not onto transformation from 
        <m>\R^4</m> to <m>\R^4</m>,
        if possible.
        If not, explain why not.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>
  
  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Two students are talking about when a matrix transformation is one-to-one.
        <blockquote>
          Student 1: If we have a matrix transformation, then we need to check that 
          <m>A\vx=\vb</m> has a unique solution for every <m>\vb</m> for 
          which <m>A\vx=\vb</m> has a solution, right?
        </blockquote>
        <blockquote>
          Student 2: Well, that's the definition. Each <m>\vb</m> in the codomain has to be the 
          image of at most one <m>\vx</m> in the domain. So when <m>\vb</m> is in the range, 
          corresponding to <m>A\vx=\vb</m> having a solution, then there is exactly one 
          solution <m>\vx</m>.
        </blockquote>
        <blockquote>
          Student 1: But wouldn't it be enough to check that <m>A\vx=\vzero</m> has a 
          unique solution? Doesn't that translate to the other <m>\vb</m> vectors? If 
          there is a unique solution for one <m>\vb_1</m>, then there can't be infinitely 
          many solutions for another <m>\vb_2</m>.
        </blockquote>
        <blockquote>
          Student 2: I don't know. It feels to me as if changing the right hand side 
          could change whether there is a unique solution, or infinitely many solutions, 
          or no solution.
        </blockquote>
        Which part of the above conversation do you agree with?
        Which parts need fixing?
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>
  
  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Show that if <m>T</m> is a matrix transformation from <m>\R^n</m> to <m>\R^m</m> 
        and <m>L</m> is a line in <m>\R^n</m>,
        then <m>T(L)</m>,
        the image of <m>L</m>, is a line or a single vector.
        (Note that a line in <m>\R^n</m> is the set of all vectors of the form
        <m>\vv+c\vw</m> where <m>c</m> is a scalar,
        and <m>\vv, \vw</m> are two fixed vectors in <m>\R^n</m>.)
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>
  
  <exercise>
    <introduction>
      <p>
        Label each of the following statements as True or False.
        Provide justification for your response.
      </p>
    </introduction>
        <task>
          <title>True/False</title>
          <statement>
            <p>
              The range of a transformation is the same as the codomain of the transformation.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
          <title>True/False</title>
          <statement>
            <p>
              The codomain of a transformation <m>T</m> defined by
              <m>T(\vx)=A\vx</m> is the span of the columns of <m>A</m>.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
          <title>True/False</title>
          <statement>
            <p>
              A one-to-one transformation is a transformation where each input has a unique output.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
          <title>True/False</title>
          <statement>
            <p>
              A one-to-one transformation is a transformation where each output can only 
              come from a unique input.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
          <title>True/False</title>
          <statement>
            <p>
              If a matrix transformation from <m>\R^n</m> to <m>\R^n</m> is one-to-one,
              then it is also onto.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
          <title>True/False</title>
          <statement>
            <p>
              A matrix transformation from <m>\R^2</m> to <m>\R^3</m> cannot be onto.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
          <title>True/False</title>
          <statement>
            <p>
              A matrix transformation from <m>\R^3</m> to <m>\R^2</m> cannot be onto.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
          <title>True/False</title>
          <statement>
            <p>
              A matrix transformation from <m>\R^3</m> to <m>\R^2</m> cannot be one-to-one.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
          <title>True/False</title>
          <statement>
            <p>
              If the columns of a matrix <m>A</m> are linearly independent,
              then the transformation <m>T</m> defined by <m>T(\vx)=A\vx</m> is onto.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
          <title>True/False</title>
          <statement>
            <p>
              If the columns of a matrix <m>A</m> are linearly independent,
              then the transformation <m>T</m> defined by <m>T(\vx)=A\vx</m> is one-to-one.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
          <title>True/False</title>
          <statement>
            <p>
              If <m>A</m> is an
              <m>m \times n</m> matrix with <m>n</m> pivots,
              then the transformation <m>\vx \mapsto A\vx</m> is onto.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
          <title>True/False</title>
          <statement>
            <p>
              If <m>A</m> is an
              <m>m \times n</m> matrix with <m>n</m> pivots,
              then the transformation <m>\vx \mapsto A\vx</m> is one-to-one.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
          <title>True/False</title>
          <statement>
            <p>
              If <m>\vu</m> is in the range of a matrix transformation <m>T</m>,
              then there is an <m>\vx</m> in the domain of <m>T</m> such that <m>T(\vx)=\vu</m>.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
          <title>True/False</title>
          <statement>
            <p>
              If <m>T</m> is a one-to-one matrix transformation,
              then <m>T(\vx)=\vzero</m> has a non-trivial solution.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
          <title>True/False</title>
          <statement>
            <p>
              If the transformations
              <m>T_1: \R^m \to \R^n</m> and <m>T_2:\R^n \to \R^p</m> are onto,
              then the transformation <m>T_2 \circ T_1</m> defined by 
              <m>T_2\circ T_1(\vx)=T_2(T_1(\vx))</m> is also onto.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
          <title>True/False</title>
          <statement>
            <p>
              If the transformations
              <m>T_1: \R^m \to \R^n</m> and <m>T_2:\R^n \to \R^p</m> are one-to-one,
              then the transformation <m>T_2 \circ T_1</m> defined by 
              <m>T_2\circ T_1(\vx)=T_2(T_1(\vx))</m> is also one-to-one.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>

  </exercise>
</exercises>